<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,223,248]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation box="[331,484,223,248]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" refId="ref10486" refString="Sakai, K. (2017) One new species of a new genus, Neoaxius gen. nov., in a new family, Neoaxiidae fam. nov., from the Gulf of Nicoya, Costa Rica (Decapoda, Axioidea). Crustaceana, 90 (4), 503 - 510. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 15685403 - 00003650" type="journal article">Sakai (2017)</bibRefCitation>
presented the following argument for the new genus and family: “ 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworschak &amp; Poore, 2018" authorityName="Dworschak &amp; Poore" authorityYear="2018" class="Malacostraca" family="Neoaxiidae" genus="Neoaxius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nicoyaensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Neoaxius nicoyaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[292,382,261,284]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
as described below, is very characteristic in that it possesses highly unique morphological features of the genital organs, which cannot be found in any species of any genera of the families currently included in the superfamily Axioidea. This means that this new species could not be classified under any of the genera of these families. That is precisely why the new species is to be classified under a new genus established in the present paper, as 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworschak &amp; Poore, 2018" authorityName="Dworschak &amp; Poore" authorityYear="2018" box="[255,497,405,428]" class="Malacostraca" family="Neoaxiidae" genus="Neoaxius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nicoyaensis" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[255,497,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Neoaxius nicoyaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[503,674,404,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
”. By genital organs he presumably meant the unmodified pleopod 1. Most decapods have a modified first male pleopod so this finding should have been seen as suspect to any knowledgeable reviewer as it was to us.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1196964/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" startId="2.[151,249,1839,1861]" targetBox="[151,1436,553,1821]" targetPageId="2">
