<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1961,2022]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,1005]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
Study of the 
<typeStatus box="[346,444,1961,1986]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dworschak &amp; Poore" authorityYear="2018" box="[484,728,1963,1986]" class="Malacostraca" family="Neoaxiidae" genus="Neoaxius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nicoyaensis">
<emphasis box="[484,728,1963,1986]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Neoaxius nicoyaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows clearly that Sakai has overlooked the small, uniramous first pleopods that are still attached (flexed on right side) on the ventrally narrow pleomere 1 (
<figureCitation box="[1252,1379,1997,2022]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,249,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,553,1821]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,553,1821]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Guyanacaris caespitosa (Squires, 1979).SMF 31563, male (holotype of Neoaxius nicoyaensis). A, pleomeres 1–5 in ventral vieW; B, detail of pleopod 1 from frame in A; C, carapace in dorsal vieW (photo: S. M. Schnedl), arroWs point to spines behind cervical groove. Scale bar: A, C = 10 mm; B = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1196964/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Fig. 1A, B</figureCitation>
). He dissected the right pleopods 2–4, interpreted one of either the third or fourth as pleopod 1 (fig. 2A) labelling the other pleopod 3 (fig. 3D) and correctly figured pleopod 2 (fig. 3B); all were erroneously stated to be from the left side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
As the ‘unique’ character used to establish the new higher taxa is based on an error, Sakai’s (2017) reasons to establish a new genus and family lack any justification. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sakai" authorityYear="2017" box="[798,902,297,320]" class="Malacostraca" family="Neoaxiidae" genus="Neoaxius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[798,902,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Neoaxius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is hereby synonymised with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sakai" authorityYear="2011" box="[1242,1387,296,319]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1242,1387,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Guyanacaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sakai" authorityYear="2017" box="[151,279,332,357]" class="Malacostraca" family="Neoaxiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Neoaxiidae</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huxley" authorityYear="1879" box="[342,434,332,357]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Axiidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
Although 
<bibRefCitation box="[315,524,367,392]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" refId="ref10486" refString="Sakai, K. (2017) One new species of a new genus, Neoaxius gen. nov., in a new family, Neoaxiidae fam. nov., from the Gulf of Nicoya, Costa Rica (Decapoda, Axioidea). Crustaceana, 90 (4), 503 - 510. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 15685403 - 00003650" type="journal article">Sakai (2017: 504)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned in his remarks on the new family that the new genus is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Komai &amp; Tachikawa, 2008" authorityName="Komai &amp; Tachikawa" authorityYear="2008" box="[151,583,404,429]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Litoraxius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,266,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Litoraxius</emphasis>
Komai &amp; Tachikawa, 2008
</taxonomicName>
, he compared his new species with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Boesch &amp; Smalley" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[990,1278,404,429]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutimana">
<emphasis box="[990,1278,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Guyanacaris hirsutimana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in his table I, referring to two specimens (the 
<typeStatus box="[520,618,439,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">holotype</typeStatus>
<collectionCode box="[628,709,440,464]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">USNM</collectionCode>
137428 from British 
<collectingCountry box="[962,1049,440,464]" name="Guyana" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Guyana</collectingCountry>
and one male, 
<accessionNumber box="[1230,1368,440,464]" httpUri="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/SMF31827" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<collectionCode box="[1230,1286,440,464]" country="Germany" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34838" name="Forschungsinstitut und Natur-Museum Senckenberg" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">SMF</collectionCode>
31827
</accessionNumber>
, from Pacific 
<collectingCountry box="[236,359,476,501]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<collectingRegion box="[236,300,476,500]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Costa</collectingRegion>
Rica
</collectingCountry>
) he had dealt with earlier (
<bibRefCitation box="[658,788,476,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" refId="ref10428" refString="Sakai, K. (2011) Axioidea of the World and a Reconsideration of the Callianassoidea (Decapoda, Thalassinidea, Callianassida) Crustaceana Monographs, 13, 1 - 616. Available from: https: // decapoda. nhm. org / pdfs / 32288 / 32288. pdf (accessed 27 July 2017)" type="journal article">Sakai 2011</bibRefCitation>
). This table contains—besides the misinterpreted pleopod 1—other errors: (1) the 
<typeStatus box="[434,532,511,536]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Boesch &amp; Smalley" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[576,746,511,536]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutimana">
<emphasis box="[576,746,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. hirsutimana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a postcervical carina as figured by Boesch &amp; Smalley (1972: fig. 1) and 
<bibRefCitation box="[380,653,548,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" refId="ref10428" refString="Sakai, K. (2011) Axioidea of the World and a Reconsideration of the Callianassoidea (Decapoda, Thalassinidea, Callianassida) Crustaceana Monographs, 13, 1 - 616. Available from: https: // decapoda. nhm. org / pdfs / 32288 / 32288. pdf (accessed 27 July 2017)" type="journal article">Sakai (2011: fig. 22B)</bibRefCitation>
; (2) 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Boesch &amp; Smalley" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[718,891,548,573]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutimana">
<emphasis box="[718,891,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. hirsutimana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sometimes also possesses distinct carinae on pleomeres 1 to 5 as shown by Blanco-Rambla (1995: fig. 
<quantity box="[799,843,584,608]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" unit="g" value="11.0">11g</quantity>
). 
<bibRefCitation box="[863,1007,583,608]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" refId="ref10486" refString="Sakai, K. (2017) One new species of a new genus, Neoaxius gen. nov., in a new family, Neoaxiidae fam. nov., from the Gulf of Nicoya, Costa Rica (Decapoda, Axioidea). Crustaceana, 90 (4), 503 - 510. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 15685403 - 00003650" type="journal article">Sakai (2017)</bibRefCitation>
overlooked the prominent spines near the cervical groove (see 
<figureCitation box="[424,508,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,249,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,553,1821]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,553,1821]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Guyanacaris caespitosa (Squires, 1979).SMF 31563, male (holotype of Neoaxius nicoyaensis). A, pleomeres 1–5 in ventral vieW; B, detail of pleopod 1 from frame in A; C, carapace in dorsal vieW (photo: S. M. Schnedl), arroWs point to spines behind cervical groove. Scale bar: A, C = 10 mm; B = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1196964/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
) that are typical of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Squires" baseAuthorityYear="1979" box="[728,877,621,644]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caespitosa">
<emphasis box="[728,877,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. caespitosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sakai" authorityYear="2011" box="[199,344,656,679]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,344,656,679]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Guyanacaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from two species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Boesch &amp; Smalley" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[664,830,655,680]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutimana">
<emphasis box="[664,830,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. hirsutimana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Atlantic (Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[1135,1220,655,680]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<collectingCountry box="[1135,1220,655,680]" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
to British 
<collectingCountry box="[1340,1429,656,680]" name="Guyana" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Guyana</collectingCountry>
) and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Squires" baseAuthorityYear="1979" box="[198,347,693,716]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caespitosa">
<emphasis box="[198,347,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. caespitosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Pacific (
<collectingRegion box="[550,637,692,717]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<collectingCountry box="[550,637,692,717]" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[674,790,692,717]" name="Colombia" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Colombia</collectingCountry>
). 
<bibRefCitation box="[808,1064,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" refId="ref11034" refString="Squires, H. J. (1979) Axiopsis (Axiopsis) caespitosa (Thalassinidea, Axiidae), a new species from the Pacific coast of Colombia. Canadian Journal of Zoology, 57, 1884 - 1891. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / z 79 - 207" type="journal article">Squires (1979: table 1)</bibRefCitation>
outlined the differences between the two species, noting that the median carina of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Boesch &amp; Smalley" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[717,885,727,752]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutimana">
<emphasis box="[717,885,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. hirsutimana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has eight spines while that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Squires" baseAuthorityYear="1979" box="[1239,1389,728,752]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caespitosa">
<emphasis box="[1239,1389,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. caespitosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has three. The specimen (
<collectionCode box="[401,502,764,788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">MZUCR</collectionCode>
1665-01) attributed to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Squires" baseAuthorityYear="1979" box="[774,926,765,788]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caespitosa">
<emphasis box="[774,926,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. caespitosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Dworschak (2013) had more than three. That this specimen was found only about 
<quantity box="[620,691,799,824]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" unit="km" value="30.0">30 km</quantity>
west of the 
<typeStatus box="[828,876,800,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dworschak &amp; Poore" authorityYear="2018" box="[1005,1169,801,824]" class="Malacostraca" family="Neoaxiidae" genus="Neoaxius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nicoyaensis">
<emphasis box="[1005,1169,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">N. nicoyaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
supports the synonymy of the two species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<bibRefCitation box="[199,342,871,896]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" refId="ref10428" refString="Sakai, K. (2011) Axioidea of the World and a Reconsideration of the Callianassoidea (Decapoda, Thalassinidea, Callianassida) Crustaceana Monographs, 13, 1 - 616. Available from: https: // decapoda. nhm. org / pdfs / 32288 / 32288. pdf (accessed 27 July 2017)" type="journal article">Sakai (2011)</bibRefCitation>
reported two specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Boesch &amp; Smalley" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[651,817,871,896]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutimana">
<emphasis box="[651,817,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. hirsutimana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(the Atlantic species) from the Pacific, one from Golfo Dulce, 
<collectingCountry box="[234,357,908,933]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<collectingRegion box="[234,298,908,932]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Costa</collectingRegion>
Rica
</collectingCountry>
(
<accessionNumber box="[374,513,908,932]" httpUri="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/SMF31827" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">
<collectionCode box="[374,432,908,932]" country="Germany" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34838" name="Forschungsinstitut und Natur-Museum Senckenberg" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">SMF</collectionCode>
31827
</accessionNumber>
) and one from 
<collectingCountry box="[691,742,909,932]" name="Peru" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<collectionCode box="[759,845,908,932]" country="Netherlands" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34992" name="National Museum of Natural History, Naturalis" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">RMNH</collectionCode>
<accessionNumber box="[853,948,908,933]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/D31563" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">D31563</accessionNumber>
). We could not study those specimens, but they are certainly attributable to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Squires" baseAuthorityYear="1979" box="[532,684,944,968]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caespitosa">
<emphasis box="[532,684,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">G. caespitosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Sakai’s (2011) account with almost identical diagnosis for both species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sakai" authorityYear="2011" box="[269,414,981,1004]" class="Malacostraca" family="Axiidae" genus="Guyanacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[269,414,981,1004]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="64">Guyanacaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows that he was not aware of their differences.
</paragraph>
